title: Effective and Ineffective Traits in College Instructors as Ranked by College Students
Effective and Ineffective Traits in College Instructors as Ranked by College Students
text:
Method

What makes a good instructor, and what makes a bad instructor?

515 participants took part in a study to answer this question and of them, 381 finished the study.
Participants were given a list of 31 Effective traits and 26 Ineffective traits and asked to rank them in order of importance from 1 to 10.

Effective Traits


Code
# All Effective Traits
tibble(
  Effective = trait_names$traits[1:31]
) |> 
  hux() |> 
  theme_article()

Fig 1. Bar Chart showing Top 10 Effective and Ineffective Values




Code
at_cln_sort |> 
  mutate(
    fill = case_when(
      type == "Effective" & n == max(n) ~ "#E39774",
      type == "Ineffective" & shift == min(shift) ~ "#326273",
      .default = "grey"
    )
  ) |> 
  ggplot(aes(fct_reorder(traits,shift),shift, 
             shift, fill = fill)) + 
  geom_col() + 
  coord_flip() + 
  theme_minimal() + 
  labs(
    x = "",
    y = "\nTrait Ranking",
    fill = "Trait Type",
    title = "What Makes A Good (or Bad) Instructor?",
    subtitle = "*<span style = 'color: #E39774'>**Effective instructors**</span> care about their students and are approachable<br>
    while <span style = 'color: #326273'>**Ineffective instructors**</span> are unapproachable and inconsistent*<br>",
  ) +
  theme(
    plot.title.position = "plot",
    plot.title = element_markdown(size = 15,
                                  face = "bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_markdown()
  ) +
  scale_fill_identity() 




Qualitative Analysis
The visualization below represents the frequency of certain words in the comment section for the effective trait portion of the study. Word size is related to the frequency of words used in participant comments. Words with high frequency (to, and, the, are, I, etc.) are removed for further context.
Note: Relative word size is not an accurate display of importance, however, it can visually indicate some thematic elements.


Code
ef_wc <- 
  et_cln |>
  select(comments) |>
  unnest_tokens(word,comments) |>
  group_by(word) |>
  count(sort = TRUE) |>
  anti_join(stop_words, by = join_by(word))

ef_wc |> 
  wordcloud2()




Fig 2. Wordcloud of word frequency in comments for Effective Traits


The visualization below represents the frequency of certain words in the comment section for the ineffective trait portion of the study.


Code
inef_wc <- 
  et_cln |>
  select(comments_0) |> 
  unnest_tokens(word,comments_0) |> 
  group_by(word) |> 
  count(sort = TRUE) |> 
  anti_join(stop_words, by = join_by(word))

inef_wc |> 
  wordcloud2()




Fig 3. Wordcloud of word frequency in comments for Ineffective Traits



Qualitatively Comparing Comments for Effective and Ineffective Trait Rankings
Participants wrote more than 1.5x for the effective traits than the amount they wrote for the ineffective traits.


Code
ef_t <- 
  ef_wc |> 
  ungroup() |> 
  summarise(total = sum(n)) 

inef_t <- 
  inef_wc |> 
  ungroup() |> 
  summarise(total = sum(n))

ef_t |> 
  bind_rows(inef_t) |> 
  mutate(trait = c("Effective","Ineffecive")) |> 
  ggplot(aes(trait, total, fill = trait)) + 
  geom_col() +
  labs(
    x = "",
    y = ""
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "none"
  ) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#E39774","#326273"))











Semantic Analyses
The figure below shows the overall count for words with negative (poor, confusing, disrespectful) and positive words (patient, comfortable, effective) participants used in their comments.


Code
ef_s <- 
  ef_wc |> 
  inner_join(get_sentiments(lexicon = "bing")) |> group_by(sentiment) |> 
  count(sort = T) |> 
  mutate(type = "Effective")


Joining with `by = join_by(word)`


Code
inef_s <- 
  inef_wc |> 
  inner_join(get_sentiments(lexicon = "bing")) |> 
  group_by(sentiment) |> 
  count(sort = T)|> 
  mutate(type = "Ineffective")


Joining with `by = join_by(word)`


Code
ef_s |> 
  bind_rows(inef_s) |> 
  ggplot(aes(type,n,fill = sentiment)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity",
           position = "dodge") +
  theme_minimal() +
  ylim(0,200) +
  labs(
    x = "\nTrait Type",
    y = "",
    fill = "Sentiment"
  ) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#133B2E","#91475F"))












Demographics
The table below shows the demographic make-up of the participants. Regional data has been modified to only show the region name and not the states that compose it.


Code
demo <- 
  all_traits |> 
  select(gender,year,age,school,geographical_region) |> 
  mutate(
    # Get Labels of Demographic variables
    Gender = sjlabelled::get_labels(all_traits$gender)[all_traits$gender],
    Year = sjlabelled::get_labels(all_traits$year)[all_traits$year],
    School = sjlabelled::get_labels(all_traits$school)[all_traits$school],
    Region = sjlabelled::get_labels(all_traits$geographical_region)[all_traits$geographical_region],
    Region = str_remove_all(Region, "\\(.*\\)"),
    Region = trimws(Region),
    Age = sjlabelled::get_labels(all_traits$age)[all_traits$age])

# Apply Custom Function
gen <- discrete_tab(demo,"Gender")

year <- discrete_tab(demo,"Year")

school <- discrete_tab(demo,"School")

geo <- discrete_tab(demo,"Region")

age <- discrete_tab(demo,"Age")

gen |> 
  add_rows(year) |> 
  add_rows(school) |> 
  add_rows(geo) |> 
  add_rows(age) |> 
  # Add Header Row
  insert_row("Variable","N","Percent") |> 
  set_top_border(row = 1:3,1:3) |> 
  set_align(col = 1, value = "left") |>  
  set_align(1,1,"center") |> 
  set_bottom_border(row = nrow(all), col = ncol(all), value = .4)
